@Node "Program startup" "AddressAssist.guide/Program startup"
@Next "Quick Tour"
@Prev "Overview"
@Toc "Overview"

Program startup
===============

To start AA, just double-click on the application's icon (or the icon
of a project file) on the Workbench. From the shell, you may type

	AddressAssist [<ProjectFile>]

The path of the project file is the only parameter supported when
starting AA. A `Project File' contains all record data of the database
as well as specific data for the database and application setup
(@{"Preferences" Link "Preferences"}).

If the application doesn't start, some of the needed files may not be
present on your system. Please refer to @{"Installation" Link "Installation"} in this manual in
this case.

@{b}Note:@{ub} The program stack must be set to 40000 in order to use
AA without problems.


@EndNode

@Node "Quick Tour" "AddressAssist.guide/Quick Tour"
@Next "Help!"
@Prev "Program startup"
@Toc "Overview"

Quick Tour
==========

After startup, the `main window' is opened. There you may recognize two
different control groups:

   * The @{b}Image-button toolbar@{ub} at the top of the main window
     provides quick access to the most important functions. See
     @{"Image-button toolbar" Link "Image-button toolbar"}, for a description of the button's use.

   * The lower part of the window is covered by the @{b}Database View
     Group@{ub}. There are two types of database views available: The
     @{i}Database List view@{ui} and the @{i}Record Form view@{ui}. See
     @{"Database view" Link "Database view"}, for more information about this important topic.

Furthermore, there is a menu strip attached to the main window, which
provides access to *all* available functions in the application
(@{"Menu Reference" Link "Menu Reference"}):

   * @{b}Project Menu@{ub}: database related functions.

   * @{b}View Menu@{ub}: view related functions.

   * @{b}Record Menu@{ub}: record (say address) related functions.

   * @{b}Selection Menu@{ub}: database selection related functions.

   * @{b}Process Menu@{ub}: special functions like database
     import/export, sorting and the preferences editor.

   * @{b}ARexx Menu@{ub}: Configure ARexx interface and execution of
     ARexx scripts.

There is a short ARexx based tutorial to AA: just click on the `ARexx
demo' menu item in the `ARexx menu'.

To load a database, select @{b}Load...@{ub} from the `Project Menu' and
choose the database filename. If the program starts the first time
after installation, a standard database will be loaded automatically.
You may make a current database to be loaded automatically after
startup by the @{b}Save path@{ub} menu item from the `Project Menu'.

After startup, all records in the database are shown in the big list
view. This is the `Database List view'. Use the `Listview format' page
in the @{"Preferences dialogbox" Link "Preferences dialogbox"} to change the format of the list view.

Switch to the `Record Form view' by double-click on a record in the
listview or use the menu item in the `View Menu' (@{"Database view" Link "Database view"}).

Now you can watch - and edit - the full record data. To edit record
data, just click in a string field, change data and press `<Return>' or
`<TAB>' to move to the next field. Save changes to the record, using
the @{b}Save record@{ub} button or the equivalent menu item in the
`Record menu'. You will be asked to save changes, if you forgot!

You may change the names of the @{i}FreeX@{ui} fields in the
@{"Preferences dialogbox" Link "Preferences dialogbox"}.

Check one of the 10 group checkmarks to assign the current record to
this group. Alternatively you may use the `Groups dialogbox' available
though the `Set/Remove groups...' menu items from the `Record Menu' to
perform this task on several records. The group checkmarks are used to
distinguish up to ten @{"Record groups" Link "Record groups"}. The names of the groups may be
changed in the @{"Preferences dialogbox" Link "Preferences dialogbox"}.

There are two more text fields available. Implemented in separate
windows, these fields feature multi-line text. Use the menu items in
the `View Menu' to open or close the field windows (@{"The remark fields" Link "The remark fields"}).

You may link other records to this current record: Think about yourself
for good uses of this feature! Just select a link alias from the
`Links:' popup to view the linked record. Add or change record links
with the buttons in the `Links:' popup and the `Record links dialogbox'.
See @{"Record links" Link "Record links"}, for more infos about this extra feature.

Switch back to the @{b}Database List view@{ub} by using the second
button from the right on the Image-button bar (beside the Help! button)
or the menu item in the `View menu'.

To move to other records of the database, use the cursor keys -
`<shifted>' to move to the first or last record - or the equivalent
buttons in the @{b}Image-button toolbar@{ub}. You may like to search
for a record by a key. Use the @{b}Find...@{ub} and @{b}Find next@{ub}
menu items to enter a search string and find the record.

A very useful feature of AA is the ability to define a
@{"Record selection" Link "Record selection"}. Selected records may be printed, exported, edited or
viewed separate from the other, say unselected, records. A record may
be selected just by checking the `checkbox' to the right of the
@{i}Salutation@{ui} field. In the @{b}Database List view@{ub}, selected
records are marked with a star ('`*''). You may add or remove multiple
records to/from a selection by using the four buttons in the
@{b}Database List view@{ub}: @{i}All@{ui}, @{i}None@{ui},
@{i}Toggle@{ui} current or by a @{i}Filter@{ui}. The @{b}Filter...@{ub}
item opens the @{"Filter dialogbox" Link "Filter dialogbox"}, where you may filter records to or
from a selection by `text-pattern' or `group' match.

Use the @{b}Sort...@{ub} menu item in the `Process menu' to change sort
directions and sort indices of the database in memory (@{"Database sort" Link "Database sort"}).

From AA you may print you record data in many different ways: there are
templates available to print columnar record lists or label sheets.
Most of the parameters that define the output may be varied: the most
imortant are the selective record field print and ordering, the output
text styles and formats as well as headers and footers. See
@{"Database print" Link "Database print"}, for further information about this interesting and
powerful feature.

AA stores databases to disk by default in so called @{i}project
files@{ui}, which are only readable by AA.

If you like to transfer data to other database programs, please take a
look at the powerful Import/Export functions. AA provides a variety of
possibilities to exchange data with other applications. These
possibilities are included in the @{"Import and Export" Link "Import and Export"} functions. You may
interchange data in plain ASCII files, readable by most other database,
wordprocessors and spreadsheet applications on the AMIGA and on all
other platforms. The format of the transfer files may be changed to
your needs using the @{"Transfer ASCII dialogbox" Link "Transfer ASCII dialogbox"}. You may save and reload
a current enchange setup. Some predefined setups are provided.

If you ever need a hint how to solve a specific task in AA, just make
use of MUI's bubble hekp feature or the @{b}Help@{ub} key (@{"Help!" Link "Help!"})


@EndNode

@Node "Help!" "AddressAssist.guide/Help!"
@Next "Image-button toolbar"
@Prev "Quick Tour"
@Toc "Overview"

Help!
=====

Help on Help! If you press the `<Help>' key or the equivalent button on
the @{"Image-button toolbar" Link "Image-button toolbar"}, AA will open this file as
@{b}Online-Help@{ub}. If the application doesn't find the helpfile
(`AddressAssist .guide'), it opens a filerequester window to select the
path of the helpfile.

To @{b}change the help file path@{ub}, just press `<shift> <Help>':
this will open the filerequester window. The path of the helpfile is
saved automatically.

Since MUI 3, AA supports @{b}Bubble help@{ub}! Just move the mouse
pointer to a control (button, text-field, list-field...) or control
group, wait and you'll get infos about the purpose of this control.


@EndNode

@Node "Image-button toolbar" "AddressAssist.guide/Image-button toolbar"
@Next "Database format"
@Prev "Help!"
@Toc "Overview"

Image-button toolbar
====================

The buttons on the toolbar are structured in 7 groups/individuals. From
the left to the right, the following functions are accessible through
the buttons:

*@{b} New@{ub}
*@{b} Open@{ub}
*@{b} Save@{ub}
     Create a new, load and save a database (@{"Project Menu" Link "Project Menu"}).

*@{b} Print@{ub}
     Print database, a selection of records or only the current record
     (@{"Database print" Link "Database print"}).

*@{b} New record@{ub}
*@{b} Save record@{ub}
*@{b} Duplicate record@{ub}
*@{b} Delete record@{ub}
     Create a new record, save, duplicate and remove the current record
     (@{"Record edit" Link "Record edit"}).

*@{b} '|<'@{ub}
*@{b} '<'@{ub}
*@{b} '>'@{ub}
*@{b} '>|'@{ub}
     Move to the first, previous, next or last record
     (@{"Database navigation" Link "Database navigation"}).

*@{b} Find...@{ub}
*@{b} Find next@{ub}
     Search records by key string (@{"Find a record" Link "Find a record"}).

*@{b} Toggle view@{ub}
     Switch between the @{"Database view" Link "Database view"} types: `Database list view' or
     `Record form view'.

*@{b} Help!@{ub}
     Get online @{"Help!" Link "Help!"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Database format" "AddressAssist.guide/Database format"
@Next "Database view"
@Prev "Image-button toolbar"
@Toc "Overview"

Database format
===============


 @{" The record fields " Link "The record fields"} 			Record data fields.
 @{" User definable fields " Link "User definable fields"} 		The FreeX fields.
 @{" The remark fields " Link "The remark fields"}  			The Remark field windows.


@EndNode

@Node "The record fields" "AddressAssist.guide/The record fields"
@Next "User definable fields"
@Prev "Database format"
@Toc "Database format"

The record fields
-----------------

AA's database consists of 16 record fields. In the context of AA and
this manual, an 'address' is referenced as *record*.

`Salutation'
     @{i}length: 255 chars@{ui}; useful for printing address labels

`Name'
`Name2'
     @{i}length: 255 chars each@{ui}; first and last name or company
     name

`Phone1'
`Phone2'
     @{i}length: 255 chars each@{ui}; useful for phone and fax numbers

`Street1'
`Street2'
     @{i}length: 255 chars each@{ui}; street and number or additional
     information

`Place'
     @{i}length: 255 chars each@{ui}; post code, city and state
     information

`Free1'
`Free2'
`Free3'
`Free4'
     @{i}length: 255 chars each@{ui}; user definable fields, see below.

`Code'
     @{i}length: 255 chars@{ui}; useful f.e. to distinguish between
     several classes of addresses by using an appropriate character
     code for each of the different classes. Classes of addresses may
     be, for example, private or business addresses and hotels,
     restaurants or companies.

`Group'
     10 Checkbox buttons to distinguish of up to 10 groups of record
     data (@{"Record groups" Link "Record groups"}).

`Remark1'
`Remark2'
     2 multi-line text fields of unlimited length for use as
     annotations (@{"The remark fields" Link "The remark fields"}).


@EndNode

@Node "User definable fields" "AddressAssist.guide/User definable fields"
@Next "The remark fields"
@Prev "The record fields"
@Toc "Database format"

User definable fields
---------------------

Use the four `FreeX' fields to your own desire by name them to your
choice and then use them consequently. The field names may be changed
in the @{"Preferences dialogbox" Link "Preferences dialogbox"}.


@EndNode

@Node "The remark fields" "AddressAssist.guide/The remark fields"
@Prev "User definable fields"
@Toc "Database format"

The remark fields
-----------------

There are two 2 remark fields with unlimited text length available. The
are implemented in separate windows - the @{"Remark windows" Link "Remark windows"} - and a text
entry may consist of multiple lines. You may open or close the windows
using the @{b}Remark Window x@{ub} items in the @{"View Menu" Link "View Menu"}. Just type
text into the text field of the window, it will be stored to the
current record data in the same way the other fields are.

Note: The multi-line remark fields are available only if the
@{"Textfield gadget" Link "Textfield gadget"} is installed on your system.


@EndNode

@Node "Database view" "AddressAssist.guide/Database view"
@Next "Database navigation"
@Prev "Database format"
@Toc "Overview"

Database view
=============


 @{" Database view types " Link "Database view types"} 		List and Form view
 @{" Remark windows " Link "Remark windows"} 		2 Annotation fields in separate windows
 @{" Selective record view " Link "Selective record view"} 	Change the set of displayed records


@EndNode

@Node "Database view types" "AddressAssist.guide/Database view types"
@Next "Remark windows"
@Prev "Database view"
@Toc "Database view"

Database view types
-------------------

AA provides two types of database view: The @{b}Database List
view@{ub} and the @{b}Record Form view@{ub}. While the `List view' is
used for quick overview and access to all the records in the database,
you may watch and edit detailed record information in the `Record Form
view'.

There are several ways to switch between the two views:
   * From `Database List view', the highlighted record may be accessed
     directly by `<Double-Click>' in the list view gadget. You may also
     use the @{b}Edit@{ub} menu item from the `Record menu' to perform
     the same action.

   * Use the @{b}View@{ub} button on the @{"Image-button toolbar" Link "Image-button toolbar"} to toggle
     the view type easily.

   * From the `View menu', you may also use the @{b}List view@{ub} or
     @{b}Form view@{ub} menu items or there shortcuts to switch the
     view type.

   * Additionally, the use of the @{"Record edit" Link "Record edit"} functions will change the
     view to `Record Form view' automatically.

Change the format of the `Database List view' in the `Listview format'
page of the @{"Preferences dialogbox" Link "Preferences dialogbox"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Remark windows" "AddressAssist.guide/Remark windows"
@Next "Selective record view"
@Prev "Database view types"
@Toc "Database view"

Remark windows
--------------

Each of the two remark windows contain a text field gadget for the
remarks fields (@{"The remark fields" Link "The remark fields"}). Use @{b}Remark window 1@{ub} and
@{b}Remark window 2@{ub} in the `View menu' to toggle availabilty of -
open or close - the remark windows, as you need them. The availability
of these windows will be stored as preferences data in the database
project files.


@EndNode

@Node "Selective record view" "AddressAssist.guide/Selective record view"
@Prev "Remark windows"
@Toc "Database view"

Selective record view
---------------------

In a database with a huge number of records included, one may easily
fail to overview a set of records needed at the time. Use the @{"View Menu" Link "View Menu"}
to change the set of records that should be displayed at a time:
@{b}View all records@{ub}, @{b}View only selected@{ub} and @{b}View
only unselected@{ub} and @{b}View by groups...@{ub}. The later opens
the @{"Group dialogbox" Link "Group dialogbox"} and lets you select the records to be displayed by
their group assignment. Use the @{b}View groups:@{ub} checkmark bar in
the `List view' for a quick access to this function. See @{"Record groups" Link "Record groups"},
for more information about the use of record groups.


@EndNode

@Node "Database navigation" "AddressAssist.guide/Database navigation"
@Next "Database sort"
@Prev "Database view"
@Toc "Overview"

Database navigation
===================


 @{" Navigation controls " Link "Navigation controls"} 		How to move through the database.
 @{" Find a record " Link "Find a record"} 		Search for records by a key string.


@EndNode

@Node "Navigation controls" "AddressAssist.guide/Navigation controls"
@Next "Find a record"
@Prev "Database navigation"
@Toc "Database navigation"

Navigation controls
-------------------

The most important controls for navigating the database are accessible
through the @{"Image-button toolbar" Link "Image-button toolbar"} and through keyboard shortcuts:

`'<''
     (Shortcuts: `left' or `down' arrow); moves to the previous record.

`'>''
     (Shortcuts: `right' or `up' arrow); moves to the next record.

`'|<''
     (Shortcuts: `shift left' or `shift down'); moves to the first
     record of the database.

`'>|''
     (Shortcuts: `shift right' or `shift up'); moves to the last record
     of the database.

`'Find...' and 'Find next''
     (Shortcuts: `ramiga =', `ramiga f' or `space'); moves to a record
     by entering a key string to find it, see @{"Find a record" Link "Find a record"}.

From the `Database List view', activate a record by `<double-click>' on
a record in the listview to change to `Record Form view' and to edit
the record's details.


@EndNode

@Node "Find a record" "AddressAssist.guide/Find a record"
@Prev "Navigation controls"
@Toc "Database navigation"

Find a record
-------------

You may find a record in the database by a key string. The program
compares @{i}all@{ui} record fields of the records with the string.
Input the key string through the @{b}Find...@{ub} menu item of the
`Record menu'. After accepting, the database will examined and the
first matching record is returned an made current. The search starts at
the current record. Use @{b}Find next@{ub} to find the next record
using the actual key string.

There are equivalent buttons for these functions in the
@{"Image-button toolbar" Link "Image-button toolbar"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Database sort" "AddressAssist.guide/Database sort"
@Next "Database print"
@Prev "Database navigation"
@Toc "Overview"

Database sort
=============

A database may be sorted in 3 levels by different @{i}indices@{ui} and
in both, `ascending' and `descending', @{i}directions@{ui}. The default
primary sort mode is `ascending' indexed by `Name'. 2nd is `ascending'
indexed by `Name2' and 3rd is `ascending' indexed by `Place'. Change
the sort modes in the @{"Sort dialogbox" Link "Sort dialogbox"}.

The currently active primary sort mode is displayed in the title bar of
the main window.


@EndNode

@Node "Database print" "AddressAssist.guide/Database print"
@Next "Record edit"
@Prev "Database sort"
@Toc "Overview"

Database print
==============

AA sports a powerful print interface which enables you to print your
record data in different ways.

These are
   * Several Record lists, with or without field names.

   * Label sheets, one or multiple columns

   * Columnar Lists, with or without field names as column title

Furthermore, all page formatting (including number of record lines per
page, header and footer lines), record field formatting (including
field order, field names) and text style may be changed.

All parameters for text printing may be changed in the @{b}Print
dialogbox@{ub}.  See @{"Print dialogbox" Link "Print dialogbox"}, for detailed information about
setting up the print parameters. Print setups may be loaded & saved.
This way a good setup may be reused later again.

Please, try out the provided example setups to learn about the power of
the printer interface.


@EndNode

@Node "Record edit" "AddressAssist.guide/Record edit"
@Next "Record groups"
@Prev "Database print"
@Toc "Overview"

Record edit
===========

The Record edit functions include all available commands for working on
and with individual records. All of them are available through the
@{b}Record menu@{ub}. Some have an equivalent button on the toolbar.
See @{"Record Menu" Link "Record Menu"}, for detailed infos.


@EndNode

@Node "Record groups" "AddressAssist.guide/Record groups"
@Next "Record selection"
@Prev "Record edit"
@Toc "Overview"

Record groups
=============

Records may be assigned to one or several groups. In AA, up to 10
record groups are distinguished. This adds structural information to
your database. Record groups may be selected and shown separate from
the other records. There are two methods to change the group assignment
of the records. Use the checkboxes in the `Record form view', if you
like to change only the current record. To modify several records, say
assign a set of group to these records, use the @{"Group dialogbox" Link "Group dialogbox"} to
simplify this process.


@EndNode

@Node "Record selection" "AddressAssist.guide/Record selection"
@Next "Record links"
@Prev "Record groups"
@Toc "Overview"

Record selection
================

A special feature of AA is the capability to create a selection of
records. A selection of records may be treated (print, export, assign
groups) separate to all other records of the database. Whether a record
is selected can be seen from the star `*' preceeding each record in the
listview gadget of the `Database List view' or by the checked checkmark
gadget on the top right of the `Record Form view'.

All selection related functions are collected in the @{"Selection Menu" Link "Selection Menu"}.
Use the 4-button bar below the listview gadget in the `Database List
view' to edit record selections.


@EndNode

@Node "Record links" "AddressAssist.guide/Record links"
@Next "Record template"
@Prev "Record selection"
@Toc "Overview"

Record links
============

Record links are an all new feature brought to database applications on
the AMIGA: A record link is a shortcut (or an alias) to another record,
which is linked to a specific record. As many such record aliases may
be added to one record, `Record links' introduce a new and very useful
way to structure your database. Think about yourself for applications
for this interesting new feature; there are plenty of them.

Select a `Record link' entry from the listview on the `Links:' popup to
display linked record data. Switch back to @{b}<Original>@{ub} to view
the original record.

Note: Record data diplayed as a link may not be edited for now: it is
read only! This may change in the future.

Record links are controled from the `Links:' popup on the formview page:

Use the @{b}Add@{ub} button and then select and name a record in the
`Links dialogbox' to create a new record link.

Use the @{b}Edit@{ub} button to change the highlighted record link.

Use the @{b}Remove@{ub} button to remove the highlighted record link.


@EndNode

@Node "Record template" "AddressAssist.guide/Record template"
@Next "Import and export"
@Prev "Record links"
@Toc "Overview"

Record template
===============

The record template function gives you the possibility to easily add
new records, which have some data in some record fields common. F.e. if
you have a couple of addresses in the same town, country and of the
same type, you can create a record Template with the common data, and
then use the template when you create new records. The template
includes all data of the record text fields, the group field and the
selection field. Data of the remark fields are not saved in the
template.

Use the @{b}Use Template@{ub} and the @{b}Save current as Template@{ub}
menu items from the `Record menu' together with the @{b}New record@{ub}
function, if you like to apply templates. See @{"Record menu" Link "Record menu"}, for detailed
information.


@EndNode

@Node "Import and export" "AddressAssist.guide/Import and export"
@Prev "Record template"
@Toc "Overview"

Import and export
=================


 @{" Import-Export selection " Link "Import-Export selection"} 	Transfer record selections.
 @{" Import-Export ASCII " Link "Import-Export ASCII"} 		Transfer data with other applications.
 @{" Import-Export Casio " Link "Import-Export Casio"} 	Transfer data with Casio SF xx00 palmtops


@EndNode

@Node "Import-Export selection" "AddressAssist.guide/Import-Export selection"
@Next "Import-Export ASCII"
@Prev "Import and export"
@Toc "Import and export"

Import/Export selection
-----------------------

To use only a part of the current database in a second stand-alone
database, export a defined selection by using the @{b}Export...@{ub}
function from the `Selection menu'. In the same way, other AA database
files may be imported. (@{b}Import...@{ub} function from `Selection
menu'). When importing from a database file, only the record data will
be read from the file; preferences data of the current database in AA
will left untouched.

Compared to ASCII Transfer, the main difference when importing a
previously exported selection is that the structural data, such as
record groups and record links will be preserved.


@EndNode

@Node "Import-Export ASCII" "AddressAssist.guide/Import-Export ASCII"
@Next "Import-Export Casio"
@Prev "Import-Export selection"
@Toc "Import and export"

Import/Export ASCII
-------------------

To transfer data of an AA database to or from other databases or
spreadsheet application on the AMIGA (f.e. Superbase, MaxonTwist,
FinalData, FinalCalc) or on other platforms (f.e. MS Access, DBase,
Filemaker or MS Excel), you may do this by using ASCII files.

Wordprocessors, such as Wordworth and FinalWriter/Copy on the Amiga and
MS Word or Wordperfect support so called `Merge files' to create f.e.
serial letters, which may be created by AA.

In AA, ASCII files may be read or written through the `Transfer ASCII
dialogbox'. In this dialog, there are all controls for defining the
format of the ASCII data files. A format definition may be saved to
disk and restored for later use. See @{"Transfer ASCII dialogbox" Link "Transfer ASCII dialogbox"} and
@{"ASCII file format" Link "ASCII file format"}, for detailed information about transfer options.


 @{" ASCII file format " Link "ASCII file format"} 	Format of data exchange ASCII files.


@EndNode

@Node "ASCII file format" "AddressAssist.guide/ASCII file format"
@Prev "Import-Export ASCII"
@Toc "Import-Export ASCII"

ASCII file format
.................

The use of ASCII files is not standardized. However they provide a very
flexible way of exchanging data with many other applications. In AA you
have all possibilities to define the format of ASCII files in a way
that reading or writing of most types of exchange files is easily
possible.

In general, the format of ASCII exchange files is as follows. The end
of each record is marked by a special char, the so called `Record
separation char'. The fields within a record are separated by another
specific char, which is called the `Datafield separation char'. In AA,
the default chars are 'LF' (ASCII 10) for record separation and ','
(ASCII 44) for field separation:

FieldA_Data1<FS>FieldB_Data1<FS>FieldC_Data1....<FS>FieldM_Data1<RS>
FieldA_Data2<FS>FieldB_Data2<FS>FieldC_Data2....<FS>FieldM_Data1<RS>
.
.
.
FieldA_DataN<FS>FieldN_Data1<FS>FieldB_DataN....<RS>

where `<FS>' and `<RS>' are the @{b}Field separation@{ub} and
@{b}Record separation@{ub} chars. `M' is the number of record fields
and `N' is the number of records.

For `Merge files', the format is only slightly different. The first
line is reserved for record field @{i}names@{ui} instead of record
field @{i}data@{ui}:

FieldA_Name<FS>FieldB_Name<FS>FieldC_Name.......<FS>FieldM_Name<RS>
FieldA_Data2<FS>FieldB_Data2<FS>FieldC_Data2....<FS>FieldM_Data1<RS>
.
.
.
FieldA_DataN<FS>FieldN_Data1<FS>FieldB_DataN....<RS>

Most important, in AA it is possible to define the record field
ordering easily yourself from within the GUI. This adds enourmous
flexibility on one hand, and comfort in use on the other hand, to the
ASCII transfer feature.

If the record entries in imported ASCII file contain less record fields
than AA provides, the missing fields will left blank. On the other
hand, if the imported ASCII datafile contains more record fields per
record, the surplus fields will be ignored.


@EndNode

@Node "Import-Export Casio" "AddressAssist.guide/Import-Export Casio"
@Prev "Import-Export ASCII"
@Toc "Import and Export"

Import/Export Casio
-------------------

AA supports direct data exchange to Casio FS type palmtop computers
(B.O.S.S. protocol). As not everybody needs this feature, it's
distributed separate to the database application in an extra product:
The @{b}Casio Exchange@{ub} package consists of the software, which is
an external module to this database application, and (optional) the
hardware: a serial link cable.

The comfortable and easy to use software allows full control of data
exchange parameters through a MUI based GUI. It supports direct upload
and download to/from the Casio with similar data control features as
available for ASCII transfer.

If you are interested, contact the author for more information and
pricing. (@{"Contacting the author" Link "Contacting the author"})


@EndNode

@Node "Menu Reference" "AddressAssist.guide/Menu Reference"
@Next "Dialogbox Reference"
@Prev "Overview"
@Toc "Main"

Menu Reference
**************


 @{" Project Menu " Link "Project Menu"} 	Database related functions.
 @{" View Menu " Link "View Menu"} 		View related functions.
 @{" Record Menu " Link "Record Menu"} 		All record related functions.
 @{" Selection Menu " Link "Selection Menu"} 	Record selection related functions.
 @{" Process Menu " Link "Process Menu"}  	Database import/export, sort and preferences editor.
 @{" ARexx Menu " Link "ARexx Menu"}  		ARexx related commands.


@EndNode

@Node "Project Menu" "AddressAssist.guide/Project Menu"
@Next "View Menu"
@Prev "Menu Reference"
@Toc "Menu Reference"

Project Menu
============

@{b}About@{ub} shows the program's `Copyright dialogbox' with
information about the current program version and revision as well as
registration status (@{"Copyright and Registration" Link "Copyright and Registration"}).

@{b}New@{ub} clears the current database in memory and you may begin to
work on a new database. You will be prompted to save changes to the old
database if necessary.

@{b}Load...@{ub} opens the filerequester window which prompts for the
filename of the address database to be loaded. Then the database will
be read from disk if possible. If there is already a database in
memory, it will be entirely cleared. You will be prompted to save
changes to it if necessary. (`ramiga o')

@{b}Save...@{ub} writes the current database to disk with its
associated filename. If there is no associated filename then you will
be prompted to input a filename by the filerequester window. (Shortcut:
`ramiga s')

@{b}Save as...@{ub} opens the file requester window which prompts for
the filename of the address database to be saved. (Shortcut: `ramiga a')

@{b}Print...@{ub} opens the `Print dialogbox', where you set all print
related parameters and print the database or only parts of it.
(@{"Print dialogbox" Link "Print dialogbox"}). (Shortcut: `ramiga p')

@{b}Save path@{ub} simply saves the path of the current database. After
startup, AA will load this database automatically.

@{b}Quit@{ub} just does what it says: Quit the program, but first ask
to save changes to the database if appropriate. (Shortcut: `ramiga q')


@EndNode

@Node "View Menu" "AddressAssist.guide/View Menu"
@Next "Record Menu"
@Prev "Project Menu"
@Toc "Menu Reference"

View Menu
=========

The @{b}List view@{ub} and @{b}Form view@{ub} items may be used to
switch database view (@{"Database view" Link "Database view"}).

Use @{b}Remark window 1@{ub} and @{b}Remark window 2@{ub} to open or
close the separate field windows (@{"Remark windows" Link "Remark windows"}).

@{b}View all records@{ub} displays all records currently available in
the database.

@{b}View only selected@{ub} / @{b}View only unselected@{ub} display
only records, which are currently selected / not selected
(@{"Selective record view" Link "Selective record view"}).

@{b}View by groups...@{ub} opens the @{"Group dialogbox" Link "Group dialogbox"} and lets you
select the records, which should be displayed, by their group
assignment. Use the @{b}View groups@{ub} button-bar in the `List view'
for a quick access to this function (@{"Record groups" Link "Record groups"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Record Menu" "AddressAssist.guide/Record Menu"
@Next "Selection Menu"
@Prev "View Menu"
@Toc "Menu Reference"

Record Menu
===========

@{b}New@{ub} cleans the display of the current record. If appropriate,
you will be prompted to save changes to the cleaned record, Then the
first string gadget is activated for input of new record data. Check
the `Record template' item to fill the fields with the data of the
Record template (@{"Record template" Link "Record template"}) (Shortcuts: `n' or `ramiga n')

@{b}Save@{ub} saves changes to the current record or adds a new record
to the database. You will be prompted automatically for the save
function, either when leaving the last datafield string gadget (`Code')
by a `return' or by selecting a function which would cause the loss of
recently changed data. (Shortcut: `s')

@{b}Edit@{ub} activates the first datafield of the current record
(`Salutation'), which is the same action as when clicking with the
mouse on this gadget or another of `current record edit group''s string
gadgets. This is useful, if the program is used only by keyboard.
(Shortcut: `e' or `ramiga e')

@{b}Duplicate@{ub} adds a new record to the database using the data of
the current record. You will be prompted by a requester to confirm this
action. (Shortcut: `d' or `ramiga d')

@{b}Delete@{ub} removes the current record from memory. You will be
prompted by a requester to confirm this unrecoverable action.
(Shortcut: `l' or `ramiga l')

@{b}Copy@{ub} copies the text data of the current record to the AMIGA's
clipboard for exchange with other applications supporting the
clipboard. (Shortcut: `ramiga c')

Check the @{b}Use Template@{ub} menu item to fill the record fields of
a new record with the record template data, instead of just clearing
the form view @{"Record template" Link "Record template"}.

Use the @{b}Save current as Template@{ub} to save the current record as
a record template. The data of the template will be stored in the
database file and is still available after a restart or reload of the
database.

@{b}Set/remove group...@{ub} opens the @{"Group dialogbox" Link "Group dialogbox"} window, with a
cycle gadget and a set of group checkboxes. The `Apply to...' cycle
gadget lets you change the set of records (`all' or `only selected
records', `current record'), which you would like to assign or remove
the assignment from specific groups. Use the group checkbox gadgets to
indicate which groups have to be assigned to. There are two methods to
change the group assignment of the records. Use the 10 group checkboxes
in the `Record form view', if you like to edit only the current record.
If you like to change similar groups assignments of several records, AA
provides this function to simplify this process:

@{b}Find...@{ub} prompts the user to input a key string. After
accepting by clicking `OK', the database will examined for the given
key and the first matching record is made the current one. The search
begins with the first record. (Shortcuts: `=' or `ramiga =')

Starting from the current record, @{b}Find next@{ub} finds the next
record in the database that matches the actual key. If there is no
actual key, this command acts like `Find...'.


@EndNode

@Node "Selection Menu" "AddressAssist.guide/Selection Menu"
@Next "Process Menu"
@Prev "Record Menu"
@Toc "Menu Reference"

Selection Menu
==============

@{b}Add all/All@{ub} selects all records of the database. (Shortcuts:
`a' or `ramiga a')

@{b}Remove all/None@{ub} deselects all records of the database.
(Shortcuts: `n' or `ramiga n')

@{b}Toggle current/Toggle@{ub} changes the selection state of the
current record. (Shortcuts: `t' or `ramiga t')

@{b}Filter.../Filter@{ub} opens the `Filter dialogbox'. (Shortcuts: `?'
or `ramiga ?')

@{b}Import/Export...@{ub} provides access to the selection
import/export functions. See also @{"Import-Export selection" Link "Import-Export selection"}.

@{b}Print...@{ub} opens the @{"Print dialogbox" Link "Print dialogbox"}, with the
@{b}Selection@{ub} cycle gadget (`Page setup') set to `previously
selected'.


@EndNode

@Node "Process Menu" "AddressAssist.guide/Process Menu"
@Next "ARexx Menu"
@Prev "Selection Menu"
@Toc "Menu Reference"

Process Menu
============

@{b}Import ASCII...@{ub} opens the filerequester window which prompts
for the filename of the ASCII data file to be imported. All records
will added to the current database. Identical records may be deleted
later by a separate function (`Remove redundant records...' from `Menu
Process'), if desirable.

@{b}Export ASCII...@{ub} first opens a dialogbox where you can specify
whether to export all records or only previously selected records
(@{"Record selection" Link "Record selection"}) from the current
database. Then you will be prompted to input the filename for the ASCII
export data file.

Use @{b}Transmit to Casio...@{ub} and @{b}Receive from Casio...@{ub} to
access the optional available @{i}Casio Exchange@{ui} package, which
provides direct reads and writes to Casio SF palmtops through a serial
link cable. Contact the author, for further information about this
interesting topic.

@{b}Sort database...@{ub} opens the `Sort dialogbox', where you can
@{i}choose@{ui} the `sort direction' and @{i}select@{ui} the
appropriate `index'. The current sort mode is displayed in the title
bar of the main window (@{"Sort dialogbox" Link "Sort dialogbox"}). (Shortcut: `ramiga r')

@{b}Remove redundant records...@{ub} examines the database for
identical records and prompts whether or not to delete found identical
records. Specify `All' to remove all record in one step without being
prompted anymore. There will be a message at the end of the operation
confirming, that there are no more redundant records in the database
memory.

@{b}Change Preferences...@{ub} opens the `Preferences dialogbox', where
you can set program and database related preferences
(@{"Preferences dialogbox" Link "Preferences dialogbox"}).

Use @{b}Change MUI Preferences...@{ub} to start the MUI preferences
editor and change the GUI parameters.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx Menu" "AddressAssist.guide/ARexx Menu"
@Prev "Process Menu"
@Toc "Menu Reference"

ARexx Menu
==========

@{b}Execute ARexx script...@{ub} opens a dialogbox, where the user is
prompted for the path of the ARexx script to be executed.

@{b}Set ARexx console...@{ub} opens a dialogbox, where the console
definition string for the ARexx console may be changed. Use standard
AMIGA-DOS keywords for the definition string as used for all AMIGA-DOS
shells. See `newshell' command documentation.

@{b}Set ARexx scripts...@{ub} opens the @{"ARexx dialogbox" Link "ARexx dialogbox"}, where the
ARexx script menu items of the `ARexx menu' are setup.

The are up to 20 @{b}ARexx script entries@{ub} available in the this
menu. The entries are dynamically added and removed following the setup
in the @{"ARexx dialogbox" Link "ARexx dialogbox"}. Use the approptiate menu item to execute an
ARexx script.


@EndNode

@Node "Dialogbox Reference" "AddressAssist.guide/Dialogbox Reference"
@Next "ARexx"
@Prev "Menu Reference"
@Toc "Main"

Dialogbox Reference
*******************


 @{" Print dialogbox " Link "Print dialogbox"} 		Printer and print interface setup.
 @{" Transfer ASCII dialogbox " Link "Transfer ASCII dialogbox"}  	Import/export ASCII text files.
 @{" Group dialogbox " Link "Group dialogbox"} 		Record group manipulation.
 @{" Filter dialogbox " Link "Filter dialogbox"} 		Record selection filters.
 @{" Sort dialogbox " Link "Sort dialogbox"} 		Database sort options.
 @{" AREXX dialogbox " Link "AREXX dialogbox"}  		Manage ARexx scripts.
 @{" Preferences dialogbox " Link "Preferences dialogbox"}  	Program and database preferences editor.


@EndNode

@Node "Print dialogbox" "AddressAssist.guide/Print dialogbox"
@Next "Transfer ASCII dialogbox"
@Prev "Dialogbox Reference"
@Toc "Dialogbox Reference"

Print dialogbox
===============

The `Print dialogbox' is accessible through

   * the @{b}Print...@{ub} menu item in the `Project menu' (Shortcut:
     `ramiga p'),

   * the @{b}Print...@{ub} menu item in the `Record menu',

   * the @{b}Print...@{ub} menu item in the `Selection menu',

   * and the @{b}Print@{ub} image-button on the `Toolbar'.

AA provides a powerful print interface which enables you to print your
records with many different ways. Using so called print
@{b}templates@{ub} formats, printing of column-titled lists or
multi-column label sheets is an easy task.

These are, how many records or record lines in columnar mode should be
printed on one sheet of paper (very useful for label printing) or
whether or not to print the record field names. For each datafield, you
furthermore may specify separately whether or not it should be printed
at all, which style should be used for printing and how many linefeeds
should be printed after each field.

Most of the print defining parameters may be changed by the user in
this dialogbox. A specific print setup may be saved and reused later.

This dialogbox consists of four pages, which are described separately:


 @{" Page setup page " Link "Page setup page"} 		Print format and templates.
 @{" Field options page " Link "Field options page"} 		Set record field order, style and format.
 @{" Header & Footer page " Link "Header & Footer page"} 	Set Header and Footer format and styles.
 @{" Printer setup page " Link "Printer setup page"} 		Output device: printer or file; paper length and margins.

To restore standard values for preferences data in this dialogbox, AA
offers both, @{i}global dialogbox@{ui} (the @{b}Default all@{ub}
button) and @{i}dialog page oriented@{ui} (@{b}Default@{ub} reset of
preferences data..

Use  `'OK'' to print with the specified setup. The `'Save'' stores
recently changes to the print parameters without printing. Leave the
dialogbox forgetting about changes with `'Cancel''.


@EndNode

@Node "Page setup page" "AddressAssist.guide/Page setup page"
@Next "Field options page"
@Prev "Print dialogbox"
@Toc "Print dialogbox"

Page setup
----------

@{b}Selection@{ub} sets the set of records to be printed: `all
records', `selected records only' or `only current record'.
(@{"Record selection" Link "Record selection"}).

@{b}LF before address@{ub} and @{b}LF after address@{ub} indicate the
number of linefeeds printed in front of / after a record.

@{b}Records per page@{ub} controls the number of record, printed on one
page ( <= 0: limited by page size). This makes it very easy to take
care of not to split a record on two pages. Use this parameter together
with @{b}Page Length@{ub} from the `Print setup' page. Set to a 0 or <0
to prevent checking the number of addresses printed on one sheet of
paper.

@{b}Template@{ub} lets you select a predefined print template.
Currently there are two templates types available: @{b}Address list
template@{ub} and @{b}Label sheet template@{ub}. If your desired print
format is not supported by these templates, use `<No Template>'. If you
have a good idea about a new template, please drop a mail to the Author
(@{"Contacting the author" Link "Contacting the author"}).

@{b}Number of columns@{ub} sets the number of print columns. This
feature is used f.e. by the `Label sheet template' to define the number
of labels printed across the page. It may also be used together with
the `<No Template>'.

Use @{b}Columns space@{ub} to set the space between the columns.

@{b}Columns width@{ub} is calculated automatically from the `Number of
columns' and `Columns space' variable as well as the `Page Width',
`Left and Right Margin' parameters (@{"Printer setup page" Link "Printer setup page"}).

Check @{b}Print header@{ub} or @{b}Print footer@{ub} to print header or
footer lines on each page. Use the @{b}Number of lines@{ub} control to
set the number of lines reserved for the header and the footer. In
fact, this is a sort of spacing between the header / footer texts and
the body of the page as the header and footer are printed on *one* line
only.


@EndNode

@Node "Field options page" "AddressAssist.guide/Field options page"
@Next "Header & Footer page"
@Prev "Page setup page"
@Toc "Print dialogbox"

Field options page
------------------

On the top of this page there is a @{b}listview@{ub} with all record
fields listed in their current print order. In addition the information
about the print format and style for each field is displayed.

There are 6 controls available to change the print format and style for
each field separately:

The @{b}'Up'@{ub} and @{b}'Down'@{ub} button change the print order of
the record fields.

The @{b}Checkbox@{ub} indicates whether or not this field is printed.
`Double-click' with the mouse on the field in the listview to perform
the same action.

The @{b}Style Cycle@{ub} changes the print style of the record field.
Choose between `Normal', `Bold', `Italic' or `Bold-Italic'.

The @{b}Linefeed Cycle@{ub} changes the number of linefeeds printed
after each record field. Select from `no LF' to up to `3 LF'.

If `no LF' is active, then the @{b}Field length@{ub} text field is used
to depermine the width of each column. This is used for columns list
printing. A value of smaller or equal zero ( <=1 ) adds only a single
`<space>' at the end of the data field text and then continues with
next field on the same line.

The controls in the @{b}Freeformat fields group@{ub} may be used to set
the parameters concering @{"The remark fields" Link "The remark fields"}: Use the @{b}Checkmark@{ub}
to indicate whether the field should be printed at all. The @{b}Number
of lines@{ub} defines how many lines are used to print the field text.
If the field data is longer than the indicated number of lines, printed
text will be truncated to the given length.

The 4 controls of the @{b}Fieldnames@{ub} group are equal to those of
the record fields in the listview above.


@EndNode

@Node "Header & Footer page" "AddressAssist.guide/Header & Footer page"
@Next "Printer setup page"
@Prev "Field options page"
@Toc "Print dialogbox"

Header & Footer page
--------------------

On this page the printing of the header and a footer lines are
controled. This page for headers and footers contains two control
groups: one for headers one for footer. These control groups themselves
are separated into three parts to input the left-aligned, centered and
the right aligned parts of the header/footer line separately. The three
input controls are as follows:

The @{b}Text input field@{ub} contains the text with control codes to
add filename and database information, date or time and page numbers to
the header/footer line. See @{"Header & Footer control chars" Link "Header & Footer control chars"} about the use
of control chars.

Use the @{b}Style@{ub} cycle field change text style: Plain,
@{b}Bold@{ub} or @{i}Italic@{ui}.

The @{b}Text preview@{ub} field shows the resulting text without
control chars in current text style.


@EndNode

@Node "Header & Footer control chars" "AddressAssist.guide/Header & Footer control chars"
@Prev "Header & Footer page"
@Toc "Header & Footer page"

Header & Footer control chars
.............................


%F	0 (default)	insert filename
	1		insert full path and filename

%T	0 (default)	insert print time (hh:mm)
	1		insert print time (hh:mm:ss)

%P	-		insert page number

%D	0 (default)	insert date (ddd mmm dd)
	1		insert date (dd.mm.yy)
	2		insert date (mm/dd/yy)
	3		insert date (dddd, dd.mmmm yyyy)

%N	0 (default)	insert total number of records
	1		insert selected number of records


@EndNode

@Node "Printer setup page" "AddressAssist.guide/Printer setup page"
@Prev "Header & Footer page"
@Toc "Print dialogbox"

Printer setup page
------------------

Change printer specific setup on this page.

The @{b}Printer@{ub} text field shows the currently selected AMIGA
preferences printer driver. Change the printer driver in the `Printer
preferences' program of your workbench distribution.

@{b}Page Length@{ub} indicates the height of the sheet of paper (in
number of lines) including Top and Bottom margin.

@{b}Page Width@{ub} indicates the width of the paper sheet (in number
of chars) including Left and Right margins.

Toggle  @{b}Line Spacing@{ub} between `six' or `eight lines per inch'.

@{b}Top Margin@{ub} is counted in number of empty lines on the top of
the paper.

@{b}Bottom Margin@{ub} is counted in number of empty lines on the
bottom of the paper.

@{b}Left Margin@{ub} indicates the left margin on the paper in number
of characters.

@{b}Right Margin@{ub} indicates the right margin on the paper in
characters, which is @{b}counted from the right side@{ub}.

@{b}Formfeed print@{ub} provides the possibility to choose, whether or
not to send a Formfeed (FF) to the printer after each printed page. Use
this switch if you have problems like always printing an empty page
after f.e. label or list print.

@{b}Output to@{ub} toggles current print output device: `Printer'
(PRT:) or text `File'.


@EndNode

@Node "Transfer ASCII dialogbox" "AddressAssist.guide/Transfer ASCII dialogbox"
@Next "Group dialogbox"
@Prev "Print dialogbox"
@Toc "Dialogbox Reference"

Transfer ASCII dialogbox
========================

The `Transfer ASCII dialogbox' is accessible through
   * the @{b}Export ASCII...@{ub} menu item in the `Process menu'.

   * and the @{b}Import ASCII...@{ub} menu item in the `Process menu'.

The body of the dialogbox is available in both export and import mode
and is used to define the file format of the ASCII transfer file. See
also @{"ASCII file format" Link "ASCII file format"}.

The @{b}Field order@{ub} group consist of a listview with the record
fields listed, and two buttons to manupulate the order of the record
fields: Use @{i}Up@{ui} or @{i}Down@{ui} to move the highlighted record
field.

The @{b}Separation chars@{ub} may indicated separetely for records
(@{b}Record separation@{ub}) and for record fields (@{b}Field
separation@{ub}). See @{"Import-Export ASCII" Link "Import-Export ASCII"}, for detailed information
about the format of the ASCII transfer files.

Check @{b}Export field names@{ub} to add the names of the record fields
at the top of the transfer file: The so called `Merge files' are often
used to exchange data with Wordprocessors.

The @{b}Preferences@{ub} group is used to @{b}Save@{ub} current file
format to disk, @{b}Load@{ub} a previously stored format or return to
@{b}Default@{ub} setup.

The additional contols depend on the mode of the dialog:

@{b}Export mode:@{ub}

The @{b}Apply to...@{ub} cycle at the top of the window defines the set
of records to export: @{i}all records@{ui}, @{i}only selected
records@{ui} or @{i}only current record@{ui}.

@{b}Import mode:@{ub}

Check the @{b}Selected@{ub} checkmark to add imported records to the
selection.

Check the @{b}Groups@{ub} checkmark to assign imported records to a set
of groups. Indicate the set of groups in the @{b}Groups dialogbox@{ub}
appearing after pushing the @{b}Groups@{ub} button.


@EndNode

@Node "Group dialogbox" "AddressAssist.guide/Group dialogbox"
@Next "Filter dialogbox"
@Prev "Transfer ASCII dialogbox"
@Toc "Dialogbox Reference"

Group dialogbox
===============

The `Group dialogbox' is accessible through
   * the @{b}Set groups...@{ub} menu item in the `Record menu',

   * the @{b}Remove groups...@{ub} menu item in the `Record menu',

   * and the @{b}View by groups...@{ub} item the `View menu',

   * the @{b}Import...@{ub} item the `Selection menu',

   * and the @{b}Import ASCII dialogbox@{ub}.

The `Group dialogbox' is used in two ways.

If invoked from the `Record menu', you may @{b}add@{ub} or
@{b}remove@{ub} the group assignments of one or several records. On the
other hand the dialogbox is used to change to set of groups for the
@{"Selective record view" Link "Selective record view"}, the selection and the ASCII import.

Use the @{b}Apply to...@{ub} cycle at the top of the window to define
to which selection of records the group assignments should be changed:
@{i}all@{ui}, @{i}only selected@{ui} or @{i}only current@{ui} record(s).

The tem @{b}Group checkmarks@{ub} are used to define the set of groups
the action should be applied to or that should be viewed.

The name of the groups may be changed in the @{"Preferences dialogbox" Link "Preferences dialogbox"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Filter dialogbox" "AddressAssist.guide/Filter dialogbox"
@Next "Sort dialogbox"
@Prev "Group dialogbox"
@Toc "Dialogbox Reference"

Filter dialogbox
================

The `Filter dialogbox' is accessible through
   * the @{b}Filter...@{ub} menu item in the `Selection menu'
     (Shortcut: `ramiga ?'),

   * and the @{b}Filter@{ub} button below the record list in the
     `Database view' (Shortcut: `F').

The `Filter dialogbox' is used to include or exclude record to or from
a selection. It consists of two main controls:

The @{b}Action@{ub} cycle at the top of the window lets you choose,
whether to include, exclude or toggle matching records to or from the
selection.

Below is the @{b}Match@{ub} page group, which provides access to the
controls of the two types of record match available:


 @{" Field string match " Link "Field string match"} 			String match of the record fields.
 @{" Group match " Link "Group match"} 				Record match to groups.


@EndNode

@Node "Field string match" "AddressAssist.guide/Field string match"
@Next "Group match"
@Prev "Filter dialogbox"
@Toc "Filter dialogbox"

Field string match
------------------

The @{b}Field string match@{ub} group consist of a number checkboxes -
one for each record field - and the actual Match string gadget at the
bottom of the group for input of the string to match one or several
record string fields. Use the checkboxes to indicate whether or not the
match operation should be applied to a record field or not.

A match would mean that the entire string `TEXT' is used up in matching
the `PATTERN' and conversely the matched `TEXT' uses up the entire
`PATTERN'.

The match function supports the following formats in the match string:
   * `'*'' matches any sequence of characters (zero or more)

   * `'?'' matches any character

   * `'\'' suppresses syntactic significance of a special character

   * `[SET]' matches any character in the specified set,

   * `[!SET]' or `[^SET]' matches any character not in the specified
     set.

A set is composed of characters or ranges; a range looks like
'character hyphen character' (as in 0-9 or A-Z).  `[0-9a-zA-Z_]' is the
minimal set of characters allowed in the `[..]' pattern construct.

To suppress the special syntactic significance of any of `'[]*?!^-\'',
and match the character exactly, precede it with a `'\''.


@EndNode

@Node "Group match" "AddressAssist.guide/Group match"
@Prev "Field string match"
@Toc "Filter dialogbox"

Group match
-----------

Use the @{b}Group checkboxes@{ub} of the `Group match' controls to
indicate whether a record should match a group or not. A record
matches, if it is assigned to a group which is checked in this control
group.


@EndNode

@Node "Sort dialogbox" "AddressAssist.guide/Sort dialogbox"
@Next "ARexx dialogbox"
@Prev "Filter dialogbox"
@Toc "Dialogbox Reference"

Sort dialogbox
==============

The `Sort dialogbox' is accessible through
   * the @{b}Sort...@{ub} menu item in the `Process menu' (Shortcut:
     `ramiga r'),

In this dialogbox, the three sort modes for the current database may be
changed. The dialogbox consists of three controls:

Use the @{b}Sort mode@{ub} cycle to select which sort mode should be
changed. There are three sort modes available.

Use the @{b}Sort direction@{ub} cycle to select, whether the current
database should be sorted in `ascending' and `descending' direction.

From the @{b}Index@{ub} list, you may select the appropriate `sort
index'.

By pushing the @{b}'OK'@{ub} button, the database will be resorted in
the desired way. Use @{b}Default@{ub} to return to the predefined
values: @{i}ascending@{ui} direction by index @{i}Name@{ui} for the
first sort mode, @{i}Name 2@{ui} and @{i}Place@{ui} as second and third
modes, each of which in ascending direction. The first sort mode is
displayed in the title bar of the main window.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx dialogbox" "AddressAssist.guide/ARexx dialogbox"
@Next "Preferences dialogbox"
@Prev "Sort dialogbox"
@Toc "Dialogbox Reference"

ARexx dialogbox
===============

The `ARexx dialogbox' is accessible through
   * the @{b}Set ARexx scripts...@{ub} menu item in the `ARexx menu'.

The `ARexx dialogbox' is used to manage the list of ARexx scripts,
executable directly froom the `ARexx menu'.

In the @{b}Available scripts@{ub} listview, the ARexx script entries
that are added to the `ARexx menu' are listed. An ARexx script entry
consists of an @{i}Alias name@{ui} and the @{i}Path name@{ui} of the
ARexx script. It is the @{i}Alias@{ui}, which is displayed as a menu
item in the `Arexx menu': click on appropriate menu item to execute
corresponding an ARexx script.

Use @{b}Drag & drop@{ub} to sort the entries in the list. The maximum
number of entries is 20.

The @{b}Add@{ub} and @{b}Edit@{ub} buttons below the listview are used
to create / change an @{i}ARexx script entry@{ui} in a separate
dialogbox. Use @{b}Remove@{ub} to delete the highlighted or all
@{i}ARexx script entries@{ui} from the list.

@{b}Save as@{ub} and @{b}Load@{ub} are used to store and restore a
specific list of @{i}ARexx script entries@{ui}. Use @{b}Append@{ub} to
append a stored list to the current one.

To close dialogbox, use

@{b}Save@{ub} to write current setup to application preferences
(@{"Preferences" Link "Preferences"}).

@{b}Use@{ub} to accept current setup, but do not store it for later use.

@{b}Cancel@{ub} to forget changes.


@EndNode

@Node "Preferences dialogbox" "AddressAssist.guide/Preferences dialogbox"
@Prev "ARexx dialogbox"
@Toc "Dialogbox Reference"

Preferences dialogbox
=====================

The `Preferences dialogbox' is accessible through
   * the @{b}Change preferences...@{ub} menu item in the `Process menu'.

The preferences items are splitted into four page groups of the
`Preferences dialogbox':

   * in the @{b}Free field names@{ub} page, the names if the four user
     definable (`FreeX') record fields may be changed.

   * Go to the @{b}Group definition@{ub} page to change the names of
     the 10 groups using the textfields on this page.

   * The @{b}Listview format@{ub} page consists mainly of two listview
     field. @{b}Drag & Drop@{ub} the fields you like to view from the
     @{b}Available fields@{ub} list to the @{b}Visible fields@{ub}
     list. Sort the visible fields by @{b}drag & Drop@{ub}. In
     addition, information concerning size of the field and column
     formatting is provided in this list.

     Use the @{b}Size@{ub} slider to change the column size in %. Check
     the @{b}Use Tab@{ub} checkmark to create a new column for the
     highlighted field. Otherwise this field's data is displayed
     together with the previous field.

     Check the @{b}Draw vertical border@{ub} checkmark to separate the
     columns in the listview by lines.

   * Use the @{b}Application@{ub} page to change program specific
     preferences: decide to save project files with an icon or have a
     'Save reminding' requester popped up when a record is changed.

To restore standard values for preferences data in this dialogbox, AA
offers both, @{i}global dialogbox@{ui} (the @{b}Default all@{ub}
button) and @{i}dialog page oriented@{ui} (@{b}Default@{ub} reset of
preferences data.

Use @{b}Save@{ub} to write setup to application preferences: the set of
preferences data is used after startup and in new database
(@{"Preferences" Link "Preferences"}).

i


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx" "AddressAssist.guide/ARexx"
@Next "Preferences"
@Prev "Dialogbox Reference"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx
*****


 @{" ARexx Introduction " Link "ARexx Introduction"}   Using ARexx with AA.
 @{" ARexx commands " Link "ARexx commands"}       Reference of all ARexx commands.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx Introduction" "AddressAssist.guide/ARexx Introduction"
@Next "ARexx commands"
@Prev "ARexx"
@Toc "ARexx"

ARexx Introduction
==================

ARexx is a powerful script language widely spread on the Amiga
computer. Many applications sport a so called @{i}ARexx interface@{ui}.
ARexx provides a standard to externally control applications and
exchange data with these applications.

In AA, nearly every command accessible in the GUI is also available in
ARexx scripts. An there are even some more.

All ARexx interface specific commands in AA are collected in the ARexx
menu. @{"ARexx Menu" Link "ARexx Menu"} in the Menu reference for more details. This way AA
sports the commodity to start ARexx scripts from a menu: You may put
favorite scripts into the `ARexx menu', where they may easily executed.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx commands" "AddressAssist.guide/ARexx commands"
@Prev "ARexx Introduction"
@Toc "ARexx"

ARexx commands
==============


